---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import Terminal from '../../components/Terminal.astro';
import { LATEST_TAG } from '../../site-version';
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Start // MCP Bridge"
  description="Wire ostk into any MCP-capable agent driver. The kernel exposes itself as an MCP server over stdio; your agent tool launches it as a subprocess and gets coordinated writes, audit, and pin caps for free."
  sectionLabel="START_PATH // MCP_BRIDGE"
>
  <p class="font-headline text-lg text-on-surface-variant italic leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-12">
    You already drive an agent. Wire ostk in as an MCP server. Your agent's tool calls become coordinated, audited, and capability-bounded writes — no UI changes.
  </p>

  <!-- What this path is -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="section-label mb-4">WHAT_YOU'LL_DO</h2>
    <div class="space-y-px max-w-2xl">
      {[
        { num: '01', step: 'Verify install + run ostk init in your project (universal steps from /start).' },
        { num: '02', step: 'Add ostk to your agent tool\'s MCP server config — one entry, two fields.' },
        { num: '03', step: 'Restart the agent tool. Confirm the kernel\'s tool surface is reachable (mcp__ostk__bash, fs_ops, read, search, ...).' },
        { num: '04', step: 'Make a write through the agent. See it land in .ostk/audit.jsonl as a hash-chained event.' },
      ].map(s => (
        <div class="bg-surface-container grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12">
          <div class="md:col-span-1 bg-surface-container-low flex items-center justify-center py-3">
            <span class="serif-text text-lg font-bold text-primary">{s.num}</span>
          </div>
          <div class="md:col-span-11 px-4 py-3">
            <span class="font-body text-xs text-secondary">{s.step}</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline mt-3 max-w-xl">
      Total time: 10 minutes. You need a working install of ostk {LATEST_TAG}+ and an MCP-capable agent tool of your choice.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Step 01: Confirm prerequisites -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="flex items-baseline gap-4 mb-6">
      <span class="serif-text text-4xl font-bold text-primary">01</span>
      <h2 class="serif-text text-2xl font-medium text-on-surface">CONFIRM_PREREQUISITES</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-lg mb-4">
      You should have <code class="text-primary">ostk</code> on your <code class="text-primary">$PATH</code> and a project initialized. From the project root:
    </p>
    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk --version
ostk {LATEST_TAG}

<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk init  <span class="text-outline"># skip if already done</span>
init: created .ostk/ ...

<span class="text-outline">$ </span>ostk mcp diag
ok: tool surface aligned with kernel seed</pre>
    </Terminal>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline mt-3 max-w-lg">
      <code class="text-primary">ostk mcp diag</code> reconciles the kernel's MCP-exposed verbs against the seeded language. If it exits 0 you're good. Source: <code class="text-primary">src/main.rs</code> (<code>McpCommands::Diag</code> dispatch), <code class="text-primary">src/commands_use/mcp_diag.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Step 02: Wire the bridge -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="flex items-baseline gap-4 mb-6">
      <span class="serif-text text-4xl font-bold text-primary">02</span>
      <h2 class="serif-text text-2xl font-medium text-on-surface">WIRE_THE_BRIDGE</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-lg mb-4">
      Most MCP clients use the same config shape: a <code class="text-primary">mcpServers</code> map keyed by server name, each entry with <code class="text-primary">command</code> + <code class="text-primary">args</code>. The canonical wiring for ostk:
    </p>
    <Terminal>
      <pre>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "ostk": {
      "command": "ostk",
      "args": ["mcp"]
    }
  }
}`}</pre>
    </Terminal>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-lg mt-4">
      Add that entry to your agent tool's MCP config file. Common locations:
    </p>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-4 max-w-2xl mt-3 space-y-2 font-body text-[11px]">
      <div class="flex justify-between">
        <span class="text-secondary">Claude Code (project-scoped)</span>
        <code class="text-primary">.mcp.json</code>
      </div>
      <div class="flex justify-between">
        <span class="text-secondary">Claude Code (global)</span>
        <code class="text-primary">~/.claude/settings.json</code>
      </div>
      <div class="flex justify-between">
        <span class="text-secondary">Cursor</span>
        <code class="text-primary">~/.cursor/mcp.json</code></div>
      <div class="flex justify-between">
        <span class="text-secondary">Other clients</span>
        <span class="text-outline">consult their MCP docs — schema is consistent</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline mt-4 max-w-lg">
      <code class="text-primary">ostk mcp</code> with no subcommand runs the stdio MCP bridge. It forwards to a running daemon when one exists; otherwise it serves in-process. You don't manage the daemon — the bridge handles both modes. Source: <code class="text-primary">src/main.rs</code> (<code>Commands::Mcp {`{ command: None }`}</code>), <code class="text-primary">src/serve/server.rs</code> (<code>run_mcp_bridge</code>, <code>bridge_stdio_to_daemon</code>).
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Step 03: Verify the surface -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="flex items-baseline gap-4 mb-6">
      <span class="serif-text text-4xl font-bold text-primary">03</span>
      <h2 class="serif-text text-2xl font-medium text-on-surface">VERIFY_THE_SURFACE</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-lg mb-4">
      Restart the agent tool so it picks up the config change. Then ask the agent to list its tools (or use the tool's MCP inspector). You should see ostk-namespaced tools appear:
    </p>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-4 max-w-2xl">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-secondary mb-3">EXPECTED_TOOLS</div>
      <div class="font-body text-[11px] text-secondary space-y-1">
        <div><code class="text-primary">mcp__ostk__bash</code> — kernel-mediated shell with audit + compression</div>
        <div><code class="text-primary">mcp__ostk__read</code> — file read with gen_table tracking</div>
        <div><code class="text-primary">mcp__ostk__fs_ops</code> — file mutation with OCC conflict detection</div>
        <div><code class="text-primary">mcp__ostk__search</code> — unified code/files/needles/decisions search</div>
        <div><code class="text-primary">mcp__ostk__lock</code>, <code class="text-primary">spawn</code>, <code class="text-primary">interact</code>, <code class="text-primary">session</code>, <code class="text-primary">tack</code>, <code class="text-primary">help</code> — coordination primitives</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline mt-4 max-w-lg">
      Tool count varies by kernel version — run <code class="text-primary">ostk mcp diag</code> for the authoritative list. Names are namespaced as <code class="text-primary">mcp__&lt;server&gt;__&lt;tool&gt;</code> by the MCP client, so <code class="text-primary">mcp__ostk__bash</code> is the bash verb routed through your <code class="text-primary">ostk</code> server entry.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Step 04: First write -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="flex items-baseline gap-4 mb-6">
      <span class="serif-text text-4xl font-bold text-primary">04</span>
      <h2 class="serif-text text-2xl font-medium text-on-surface">FIRST_WRITE</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-lg mb-4">
      Have the agent make a small file edit. Then in your terminal, watch the audit chain:
    </p>
    <Terminal>
      <pre><span class="text-outline">$ </span>tail -f .ostk/audit.jsonl
{`{"event":"tool.fs_ops","path":"src/lib.rs","gen_before":4,"gen_after":5,"writer":"claude-code-1","ts":"2026-04-26T19:42:11Z","prev_hash":"...","sig":"..."}
{"event":"tool.bash","cmd":"cargo check","exit_code":0,"duration_ms":2841,...}`}</pre>
    </Terminal>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary max-w-lg mt-4">
      Each row is hash-chained against the previous (<code class="text-primary">prev_hash</code>) and optionally GPG-signed (<code class="text-primary">sig</code>). The agent's writes flow through ostk's gen_table, so two agents editing the same file get a CAS conflict instead of a silent overwrite. Capability boundaries from <code class="text-primary">.ostk/pins/&lt;name&gt;/pin.caps</code> apply uniformly — see <a href="/docs/pins" class="text-primary hover:underline">pin caps</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Troubleshooting -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="section-label mb-4">TROUBLESHOOTING</h2>
    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-6 border-l-2 border-primary max-w-2xl">
      {[
        { issue: 'Agent reports "no MCP server named ostk"', fix: 'Config file path or JSON syntax. Validate with `cat .mcp.json | jq .`. Restart the agent tool — most clients only read MCP config at startup.' },
        { issue: 'Tools listed but every call fails', fix: 'Run `ostk mcp diag` directly. If it errors, check `ostk init` ran in this project — the bridge resolves the project root by walking up from CWD looking for .ostk/.' },
        { issue: 'Writes succeed but no audit row appears', fix: 'You\'re probably writing through the agent\'s native filesystem tools, not the ostk-namespaced ones. Restrict the agent to mcp__ostk__* tools (most MCP clients have an allowlist).' },
        { issue: 'Two daemons fight for the socket', fix: '`ostk daemon stop` then re-invoke. The bridge auto-recovers from a clean socket.' },
        { issue: 'Permission errors on write', fix: 'Pin caps deny by default. Check `.ostk/pins/default/pin.caps`. T3 (no GPG identity) gets read-only by design — see /docs/trust-model.' },
      ].map(t => (
        <div class="flex gap-6 text-xs font-body py-3 border-b border-surface-variant">
          <span class="text-error w-56 shrink-0">{t.issue}</span>
          <span class="text-secondary">{t.fix}</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What's next -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <h2 class="section-label mb-4">WHAT'S_NEXT</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-px bg-surface-variant max-w-2xl">
      <a href="/docs/trust-model" class="bg-surface-container-high p-4 hover:bg-surface-container transition-colors">
        <div class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold mb-1">→ TRUST_MODEL</div>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-secondary">GPG signing, the four-tier trust ladder, how to move from T3 to T1.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/pins" class="bg-surface-container-high p-4 hover:bg-surface-container transition-colors">
        <div class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold mb-1">→ PIN_CAPS</div>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-secondary">Bound what each agent can touch. Deny-by-default capabilities.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/needles" class="bg-surface-container-high p-4 hover:bg-surface-container transition-colors">
        <div class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold mb-1">→ NEEDLES</div>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-secondary">Cross-session memory: open questions, decisions, references.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/mcp" class="bg-surface-container-high p-4 hover:bg-surface-container transition-colors">
        <div class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold mb-1">→ MCP_PROXY (outbound)</div>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-secondary">Reverse direction: have ostk-driven agents call other MCP services.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="metadata-ribbon border-t border-surface-variant">
    <span class="font-label text-[10px] text-secondary mr-4">RELATED:</span>
    <a href="/start"><Icon name="rocket_launch" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />START_HERE</a>
    <a href="/docs/architecture"><Icon name="architecture" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />ARCHITECTURE</a>
    <a href="/docs/commands"><Icon name="terminal" size="14" class="align-middle mr-1" />COMMANDS</a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
